Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his squad. Silently stepping out of his bed, he put on his combat uniform, fastened his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, taking particular care with a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he calmly exited the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. As he lit it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. The week before, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm, half the time it didn't work, as all that came out of the speakers was a faint whistling.
"Will you wake them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching on foot.
"Ouep," answered Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
" Well, first off, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Second, the first soldiers on their feet are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"you make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He held out his hand and activated a switch. An alarm rang inside the barracks, loud and piercing. He heard a commotion inside and some confusion.
"Damn it, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they'd have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my buddies from the training camp here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their squad and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company emerged en masse. They all had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, while others were more annoyed.
"Good morning everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Except your respect, sir, why do you persist in waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are lousy. And because Daybreak doesn't do lazy mornings," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We are not returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Originally, they were split into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a split company, and Cohren didn't know what to think of his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly for reasons that had motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked together under the light of the numerous lights of the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had used both aerial and ground Wild Weasel assaults to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced forward operating base outside of Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," answered Cohren as he took a drag on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he said nothing.
"Damn it. The situation is deteriorating on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming out of this place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're leaving with the first armored squad, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Shaw got us transport?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Ugh. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren placed his thumb and index finger on his throat microphone while adjusting his backpack. "All units of Exodus Company, report to the western vehicle park when you're done. We're departing with the first armored squad at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four were very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like such a long time ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then squad leaders. But Craith now commanded the second squad for a week, following the demobilization of the previous commander, who had been wounded by an elite shooter from Daybreak.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic spotted a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armored squad. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol case before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
